   abstract = {Geocaching is a global game, originated in 2000 and revolving around creating and searching caches in real locations with the use of new technological developments (like geopositioning, beacons, QR codes), therefore combining the real and the virtual worlds. Every year, geocaching enjoys increasing popularity and geocachers can look for caches on all the continents. This should come as no surprise as geocaching is used to promote places, exchange information about the local history, nature etc. Since geocaching is a game with potential to become an effective tool of place marketing communication, a question arises, what factors affect its effectiveness in this respect. The goal of this article is therefore to identify the components of the effectiveness of geocaching used as a tool in place marketing communication. The research was conducted in Poland and combined qualitative research (interviews with managers responsible for official regions’ communication) and quantitative approach (an on-line questionnaire for geocaching players). As a final result, four components of geocaching have emerged which determine the effectiveness of the game as a tool of place marketing communication, namely: Benefits, Engagement, Game structure and Social relations. Management implications: - Geocaching raises interest of the players and place managers where the game happens. - Geocaching combines virtual (technology) and real (outdoor activities) worlds. - Effectiveness of geocaching depends on Benefits, Engagement, Game Structure, Social relations. - Geocaching is seen an attractive tool of place marketing communication.},
